         <abstract>
            <p>Let $\psi(x) = \Sigma^\infty_{n=1} e^{-n^2 \pi x}$, and $\chi(u) = e^{u/2}(1 + 2\psi(e^{2u}))$. The divergent integral $2 \int^\infty_0 \chi(u) \cos tu du$ is shown to be summable for certain complex values of $t$ to the function $2\xi(s)/s(s - 1) = \pi^{-s/2}\Gamma(1/2s)\xi(s)$, where $s = 1/2 + it$, and $\xi(s)$ is the zeta-function of Riemann. The values of a resulting approximation to $2\xi(s)/s(s - 1)$ are computed and its zeros located.</p>
          </abstract>
